leans into every complexity and expertly shows how political and social biases seep into every gap between seemingly “objective facts”. Felt applicable to so many other human situations. Writing and acting really was remarkable. Deeply French.

Exactly how a sports doc should be— super well edited, tremendous violin strumming at each pinnacle moment, good balance of sports+ personal life, never before seen archival footage, good interviews, excellent pacing.

The back to back scenes of Clive confronting Julia and then Clive and Natalie in the strip club were two of the best written and acted scenes I’ve seen in a long time. Rest of film felt too closely adapted from a play, which gave it interesting pacing and world building

The dystopian experience of losing someone. This film constructs such a moody otherworldly world, with such sad scenes that also somehow always had me feeling like a jump scare could happen. Eerie score for the entire time felt overdone. The grief as refusal was poignant as was much of the dialogue, but much of it made me feel deeply unsettled. Thought it would’ve been better as an anime. Want to read the Japanese book it’s based on.
Jack black pumping his fist after a first kiss 5 min before the movie ends is an astonishingly storytelling weapon
